In .NET MAUI Shell, you can override `OnBackButtonPressed` and use the `BackButtonBehavior` Shell attached property:

```xml
<!-- EditProductPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form here -->
</ContentPage>
```

```csharp
// EditProductPage.xaml.cs
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    public bool HasUnsavedChanges { get; set; }

    public EditProductPage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BindingContext = this;
        BackCommand = new Command(async () => await TryGoBack());
    }

    public Command BackCommand { get; }

    // Handles hardware/software back button (Android, etc.)
    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            // Fire-and-forget the dialog; return true to cancel navigation
            MainThread.BeginInvokeOnMainThread(async () => await TryGoBack());
            return true; // true = cancel default back navigation
        }
        return base.OnBackButtonPressed(); // false = allow navigation
    }

    private async Task TryGoBack()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!leave) return; // user chose Stay — do nothing
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`BackButtonBehavior`** — replaces the shell back arrow with a "Cancel" label and routes taps through your `Command`, giving you full control.
- **`OnBackButtonPressed()`** — intercepts the Android hardware/gesture back button. Return `true` to cancel navigation.
- **`DisplayAlert`** — shows the confirmation dialog; navigate only if the user confirms.

> ⚠️ `OnBackButtonPressed` only fires on Android. On iOS/Windows the shell toolbar button is the primary back mechanism, which `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles. Using both together covers all platforms.
